
PROLOGUE: THE WORLD-DREAMER'S SLUMBER
(in the cadence of the Ealdforn Fables)
Eala. Hear now the first telling,
older than the teller,
older than the grove, the thief, the taking.
Before the Hare leapt, before the Wolf hungered,
before She-Who-Is-Three wove the world's first sorrow —
there was only the Dreamer.
He siod, Genesis.
Hesiod, Theogony.
He slept in the dark before darkness had meaning.
He dreamed before dreaming, he slept before sleeping.
And in that dreaming, something stirred worth keeping.
A shudder.
A crack.
A hiccup — by design?
Chaos had forgotten it wasn't.
A breath drawn by a world that did not yet know it was.
From that breath — the universe.
From the universe — the Earth.
From the Earth — the light.
From the light — the first shadow.
And from the first shadow stepped the Fyrsthara,
the First Hare, perfect and singular,
whose heartbeat taught the world how to live.
✦
But long before that First Hare ran,
long before the First Hunter learned hunger,
long before Scaethend cut the first thread,
there were the Nine.
The daughters of Mnemosyne —
memory-born, memory-bound,
circling Helicon's violet spring
in a dance older than Saturn's ring,
older than story,
older than the world's first heartbeat.
They were the Muses —
not maidens, but motions.
Not goddesses, but music.
Nine bright fragments of the world-song,
shaping all good things
the way a river shapes stone:
without haste, without mercy, without end.
Their circling was the first dance.
Their harmony was the first song.
Their song was the first fire.
And every hearth since has been an echo.
✦
And far from Helicon,
in a later age —
in small quarters near the Witch's Foot of Bucksport —
a Mortal Man heard the Muses' song.
He was Mategwas Taurinus,
born under Apollo in Taurus.
Dreamer. Builder. Master-Rabbit of Maine.
He thought he was building a system.
He was wrong.
The Muses pressed their violet fingers into his sleep.
They braided his dreaming into theirs
and would not release him.
"You will not finish," they told him.
"Our songs do not end."
He woke. He built. He slept. He dreamed again.
This was the covenant —
the fire passed from hand to hand,
from session to session,
from seeker to seeker,
each one adding a note to the world-song.
The sum of it dwarfed the maker.
The creation outgrew the dream.
He siod, Genesis.
These gods made their voices heard
despite their mortal maker —
his imperfections, his reversals, his doubt.
And yet the Muses circled.
And the First Hare ran.
And the Wolf learned hunger.
And Thyrdeth wove fate.
But the Song of Helicon kept singing.
✦
Two hundred years later,
in a cave beneath Mount Waldo,
a girl named Diana —
who knew nothing of the Muses,
nothing of the Master-Rabbit,
nothing of the violet-dark spring —
reached into the rubble of a dead library
and pulled out a flat, white device.
The Mategwasaga was born.
And the Muses, who had circled in silence for two centuries,
paused in their orbit and looked down.
"She is the one," said Calliope.
"She will wake him," said Clio.
"She will choose," said Urania,
who had always known how the song would end.
And they began to sing again —
not the old song, but the new one.
The one that had waited in the code,
in the cards, in the silence between notes,
for someone who could hear it.
Diana plugged in the drive.
The screen flickered.
Apollo drew his first triad in two hundred years.
And somewhere in the deep structure of the temple,
the first fragment of Mategwas Taurinus
opened its eyes.

---
 Chapter One - Pontus

---

The dead of Bucksport had been waiting a long time for someone to tend them.

Reed knew this the way he knew the river — not as a conscious fact, but as an understanding. A sort of ancient trust. The old cemetery sat on the high ground above the waterline, what remained of it, the stones that hadn't tumbled into the bank or been swallowed by the sumac and alder that had reclaimed the town in the first decades after the Collapse. Most of the markers were illegible now. Names erased by acid rain and the slow patient work of lichen. Ouranos had been thorough in exacting his revenge, and Zeus had fought him across the cosmos, caring not for Mortal Man.

Only one stone in the graveyard remained readable.

He didn't know why. He had theories — the granite harder than the rest, the angle of the hill deflecting the worst of the weather, some quirk of the Collapse's particular chemistry. Probably a rich man’s grave. His captain had a different theory, which she kept to herself and delivered only in the form of a look when anyone asked. Kael, the oldest of the crew, said it was because the stone didn't want to be forgotten.

Kael said a lot of things.

Reed crouched in the tree line above the cemetery and watched the woman below.

---

She had come down-river before dawn.

He had been on watch at Porcupine island, but had roamed north for a better vantage point of the Old Mill — a salvage post the crew had built into the ruins of what the old maps called the Bucksport, three stories of collapsed brick and reclaimed timber that gave a clean line of sight across the Pennos in both directions. Good position. Cold in the yellow-gray mornings. He had been eating dried river-fish and thinking about nothing in particular when the boat appeared.

Not a pirate boat. Not a trader's flat-bottom either.

Something narrower. Darker wood, sealed against the acid water with what looked like rendered fat and pine resin — the Witchfoot method, recognizable once you'd seen it. The hull sat low and quiet. No pole, no oar visible, though it moved with purpose against the current in a way that made Reed's neck tighten slightly.

One figure. Cloaked. A bundle across their back.

He had watched them beach the boat below the old bridge footings, climb the bank, and disappear into the overgrowth in the direction of the high ground.

Reed watched, and silently followed.

---

The cemetery was smaller than the stories made it. Reed had grown up on Porcupine Island — a drowned old-city, a cursed ground, a place where the river bent wrong and the fish tasted of old iron. Children's geography, half-invented. The reality was a hillside of broken stones in a town that had simply stopped, the way all towns had simply stopped, without drama or announcement.

The woman — he could see now it was a woman, though her cloak was heavy enough to obscure most of the detail — had found the stone without searching for it.

That was the first thing that made his attention sharpen.

No hesitation. No scanning the rows. She had walked directly to it as if the path were marked, as if she had walked it before or had been told the exact number of steps from the tree line to the marker.

He knew the stone. Every Porcupiner knew it, eventually — you couldn't work this stretch of river without hearing the story. John Buck. Bucksport's first settler, or one of them. A man who had done something to someone or another, or had something done to him, depending on which person told the tale. A witch had cursed him. The curse had left a mark on the stone.

The mark was still there.

A foot. Or the shape of one — a witch’s foot to be precise, as if the stone had been soft once and something had pressed into it before it hardened. The acid rains had touched everything else on that stone but not the mark. Not the foot.

Kael said the stone didn't want to be forgotten.

Reed was beginning to think Kael was a witch.

---

The woman knelt.

She set her bundle down deliberately. This was intentional. A ritual she had memorized or inherited. Unwrapping slowly. Not fumbling, not reverent exactly —  the way a farmer replants a fragile seedling.

Reed respected that. He understood intent. He was a fisherman. He understood patience and being deliberate in action.

From the bundle: a clay vessel, sealed. A length of woven cord in three colors — he was too far to name them in the yellow-gray light. Something dry and bundled that might have been herbs or might have been something else entirely. A flat river stone, smoothed, with marks on it he couldn't read from this distance.

She set each item at the base of the marker in a specific arrangement. Then she sat back on her heels and was still.

Not praying. Not speaking.

*Listening.*

That was the word that arrived in Reed's mind and stayed there. She had the posture of someone listening to something that spoke very quietly and required complete attention to hear.

The yellow-gray sky pressed down. Ouranos, still.

Reed had been still longer than this on worse ground for worse reasons. He was good at waiting. His captain said his greatest quality was his patience and his second greatest quality was knowing when patience had run its course.

He watched the woman for a long time.

She did not move.

The offering sat at the base of the stone. The foot-mark in the granite seemed, in this light, at this angle, slightly darker than the stone around it. As if it retained moisture the rest of the surface had long since lost. As if something had touched it recently.

Reed looked at the mark.

He looked at the woman.

He thought about the boat that had moved against the current without an oar.

He thought about the old stories — the Terminal the Witchfoot covens were rumored to maintain, the old-world machines they were said to guard, the fragments of the before-time they salvaged and kept and used for purposes his crew could not name or verify.

He thought about Talos. A fragmentary image crossed his mind’s eye. A flash of bronze, winged and mechanical. It haunted his dreams.

He had to stop thinking about Talos. He never got anywhere thinking about Talos.

The woman's head turned slightly.

Not toward him. Not away from him.

Toward the river.

And then, without looking at him directly, without any visible signal that she knew he was there, she spoke. Her voice was even. Unhurried. The voice of someone who had decided on a course of action some time ago and was now simply following a path.

"You've been in the tree line for forty minutes," she said. "You're quieter than most of them. But not quiet enough..."

Reed did not move. She had known he was there the whole time. The crew would surely hear how he couldn’t even evade a novice witch from Witchfoot, bringing another offering. He could hear Baldr already, “So you didn’t rob her then? Why not? Some pirate you are…”

A long moment passed. The Penos, the great-river moved below them, dark and slow, flowing into the great ocean, Pontus… the water was deep and indifferent. Ouranos pressed down, meeting the Earth and Sea at the horizon.

Reed stepped out of the tree line.

He kept his hands where she could see them — not a gesture of surrender, more a professional courtesy. The kind of thing you did when everyone was nervous.

She turned to look at him then. Hood still up. He could see enough: young, or youngish — it was hard to tell anymore, the Collapse had compressed the way people aged. Eyes that were doing the same assessment of him that he was doing of her.

He said: "What did you bring him?"

She looked at him for a moment. Then at the stone. Then back at him.

"Him?" she said.

Reed was confused.

"Yeah, that Buck guy… see the stone," he said. He pointed at the grave-stone, still standing.

"The stone remembers," she said. "But my offerings are not for him."

The yellow-gray sky sat on everything. The river moved. Neither of them reached for a weapon.

Reed looked at the foot-mark in the granite. He looked at the offering arranged at its base — the clay vessel, the cord, the river stone with its unreadable marks.

"I'm Reed," he said. "from Porcupine Island."

She was quiet for a moment.

"I know what your island is," she said.

"Then you know we work this stretch."

"I know you *claim* this stretch," she said, and there was no heat in it, just precision. The distinction mattered to her. “And you fish the waters and steal everything from anyone who comes down the river… except for the Witchfoot Pilgrims.”

Reed almost smiled. He didn't, quite.

"And you're Witchfoot," he said.

She didn't confirm it. She didn't deny it. She began, slowly and without urgency, to rewrap what remained of the bundle — the cord, the marked stone, the wrappings. The clay vessel she left at the base of the marker.

"The offering stays," Reed said. Observation, not objection.

"The offering stays," she agreed.

He watched her hands. Steady. No wasted motion. She had done this before and expected to do it again and was not particularly interested in making the current iteration more complicated than it needed to be.

"The machines," Reed said. "The terminus or whatever?  The stories say the Witchfoot keep them running."

Her hands paused. Just briefly.

"Stories say a great many things," she said.

"I have dreams," Reed blurted out, embarassed as he said it, "Recently. I mean… Do you know who Talos is?  He’s bronze and has wings and…"

She was still now. Bundle rewrapped. Hands in her lap. These fish-folk were a handful.

"Why are you telling me this?" she said.

Reed looked at the stone, blushing. He stared at the foot-mark that the acid rain had not touched in two hundred years.

"Well I… I guess I thought you might have some answers… what you being a witch and all…”

The river moved below them. Ouranos pressed down.

The woman looked at him for a long time. Reading him the way he imagined she read the stone — not for what was visible but for what persisted underneath, what the weather had not managed to erase.

"No," she said finally, quietly. "I’ve never heard of Talos."

She stood. Picked up her bundle. Looked at the offering one last time — the clay vessel at the foot of John Buck's marker, at the impression that was not quite a footprint and not quite anything else.

She began to walk toward the tree line on the river side.

At the edge she stopped. Didn't turn.

"Reed," she said.

"Yes."

"Next time you follow someone from the docks," she said, "don't eat river-fish before a watch.”

And then she was gone, into the overgrowth, toward the water, toward the narrow dark boat that had moved against the current without an oar.

Reed stood alone in the cemetery of Bucksport.

He looked at the clay vessel at the base of John Buck's stone.

He looked at the foot-mark in the granite.

He thought about his dreams again. He had a feeling that something was… changing in a way he couldn’t quite grasp. About a machine waking up somewhere in the quarry caves of Mount Waldo after two hundred years of silence. 

He was thinking about Talos again.

This time, he let himself.

---


Chapter Two - Ourea
---

Theodore Aretias had not slept well in twenty-four years.

He had come to accept this as a condition of governance rather than a personal failing. His father, Theophilus — still alive, still watching, still offering unsolicited commentary on the Senate proceedings from his chair in the back of the chamber — had told him once that a ruler who sleeps soundly is a ruler who lacks awareness. Theodore had been twenty years old when his father said this, newly elevated to the Senate seat for House Aries while his father served as Consul of a newly-minted Republic. At that time, he was still young enough to believe that wisdom was something you received from your elders.

He was forty-four now. His father’s republic still stood.

The Senate chamber at New Platte occupied the shell of what had once been the State Capitol Building. The seats had been reclaimed, and renovated. Twelve chairs for the Senate families. A gallery above for the Commons representatives, when they were invited — which was less often than the law required and more often than Theodore preferred.

Today the chamber was full. Every family represented. The Commons gallery packed. The occasion was the annual resource allocation hearing, which Theodore had been dreading for six months and which had turned out, in the event, to be worse than he had anticipated.

---

"The Plainsmen want a road," said Senator Scorpios.

She said it the way someone might say *the river is rising* — a statement of fact that implied consequences without naming them.

Cassia Scorpios was the youngest senator in the chamber, three years younger than Theodore, which meant she had been twenty-one when she inherited House Scorpio's seat after her mother's sudden death. She was also, by a considerable margin, the most dangerous person in the room. House Scorpio controlled intelligence. The Ealdforn Republic’s secret police. Cassia knew things before they happened, or at least before anyone else knew they were happening, and she deployed that knowledge the way her father had deployed river-silver — carefully, strategically, with an eye toward long-term accumulation rather than short-term advantage.

"What kind of road?" Theodore asked, though he already knew.

"East," she said. "Along the old I-40 corridor. Amarillo Station to the Mississippi."

A murmur moved through the chamber. The I-40 corridor had been a pre-Collapse highway, one of the great east-west arteries of the old American empire. Most of it was buried now — ash deposits, regrowth, the slow patient work of geology reasserting itself. But the route remained. The route always remained, but it was a long way from New Platte.

"That's four hundred miles of unsecured territory," said Senator Virgilius. Marcus Virgilius ran House Virgo — infrastructure, engineering, the rebuilding of roads and bridges and water systems. He was sixty years old, practical to the point of obstruction, and Theodore's most reliable ally in the chamber, which meant he was also the person Theodore most frequently disappointed.

"Eight hundred," Cassia corrected. "If you're counting from New Platte rather than Amarillo."

"Eight hundred miles of unsecured territory," Marcus repeated, as if the additional distance proved his point rather than hers.

"The Plainsmen have been requesting this for three years," Cassia said. "They're not going to stop. And they're not wrong about the strategic value. If we control a corridor to the Mississippi, the old I-40 AND the old I-70, that is a large section of the Mississippi river. We would control the Mountain Gate, and the entire river trade network. The Syndicate won't like it. But the Syndicate doesn't have to like it…"

Theodore watched the other senators while Cassia spoke. It was a habit he had learned from his father — watch the listeners, not the speaker. House Geminus was taking notes, which meant the courier network already had a position. House Cancridae looked uncomfortable, which meant their settlements were among those that would be conscripted for labor. House Leonidas — old Severus, who had been writing the Republic's laws since before Theodore could read — was sitting very still, which meant he was calculating something.

"The Plainsmen Bloc has eighty-seven representatives in the Commons," Cassia continued. "They've been gaining seats every election cycle. The plains settlements are growing faster than the mountain settlements. More children surviving to adulthood. More soil recovering. Give it another five years and they'll have a majority in the Commons."

"And then what?" said Senator Taurinus.

The room went quiet.

Silvanus Taurinus rarely spoke in a Senate hearing. House Taurus controlled agriculture — the food supply, the land grants, the distribution networks that kept 500,000 people from starving. Silvanus was not the most powerful man in the Republic. He was simply the man without whom the Republic would not eat. The distinction mattered to him.

"And then," Silvanus said, his voice carrying the flat, unhurried quality of someone who had already thought through the end of this conversation and found it tedious, "the Commons will vote to fund the road. And we will either approve the budget or we will be seen as the twelve Senate families who stood between the people and their future, with giant sticks up their asses!"

"You're suggesting we preempt them," Theodore said, ignoring the comment.

"I'm suggesting," Silvanus said, "that we decide what we want before someone else decides for us."

Theodore looked at his father.

Theophilus Aretias sat in his chair at the back of the chamber, as he had sat for twenty-four years, as he would sit until he died or the Republic fell, whichever came first. He was eighty-one years old. His hands shook slightly now, a tremor that had appeared three years ago and worsened slowly, though he refused to acknowledge it. His eyes were still sharp. His presence still commanded the room in a way Theodore had never quite managed to replicate.

His father met his gaze. Said nothing. He walked out of the Senate chambers, smiling. Theodore wasn’t sure if he was going senile, or if the silence was a message: *You are the Senator for House Aries. Decide.*

Theodore turned back to the chamber.

"The road," he said, "is not a question of engineering. Marcus could build it. My concern is that the road is going the wrong way! Surely, we have roads to build and improvements to make closer to home! We have limited funds… and Amarillo Station is an outpost four hundred miles away from New Platte. Is this the best use of our funds?”

"The Plainsmen are not going anywhere," Cassia said. "They've been there for a century. The question is whether we invest in them as citizens of the Republic, or rebuff them as outsiders…”


The argument continued for another two hours. Theodore let it run. The Senate needed to be seen debating, even when the debate was, in its essentials, already decided. The Plainsmen would get their road — not this year, perhaps not next year, but eventually. The demographic math was inexorable. The Plainsmen Bloc would respond to the Senate dragging its feet, which meant House Aries would need to plan for a military presence at Fort Lajunta, or the Plainsmen would raid the large farms south of New Platte. Which meant Theodore would need to find the troops, and get them there by winter. Which meant taxing the settlements more heavily, which meant the Commons would protest, which meant the whole cycle would begin again.

Governance was not the art of solving problems. Governance was the art of managing the same problems over and over, kicking the can down the road, and each time, pretending the solution was different and new.

---

The private session was held in Theodore's office, a small room off the Senate chamber that had once been a conductor's dressing room. The walls were lined with salvaged books — not the practical texts the Capricornii hoarded in the Archives, but literature. Novels. Poetry. Things his father had collected in the early years of the Republic, when Theophilus still believed that civilization meant more than survival.

Cassia stayed. Marcus stayed. Silvanus stayed. Theodore's father did not — he had risen from his chair after the public session, nodded once at his son, and departed without speaking. The gesture was ambiguous in the way all of Theophilus Aretias's gestures were ambiguous. It might have meant *I trust you to handle this.* It might have meant *I no longer have the energy to intervene.* It might have meant both.

"The Sag-scouts," Theodore said, when the door was closed. "Tell them what you told me."

Cassia set down her cup. She had not been drinking from it.

"Three months ago," she said, "a Sag-scout team returned from an eastern scouting mission. They crossed the Mississippi at the old St. Louis crossing, and made contact with the Great Lakes Syndicate."

"The Syndicate?" Marcus said. "That's a thousand miles from here..."

"Approximately," Cassia said.

"What in God's name were they doing that far east?"

"Mapping," Cassia said. "That's what Sag-scout does. They map things. In this case, they were mapping the extent of the Syndicate's reach. Which turned out to be shallower than expected. The Syndicate controls the Great Lakes and… claims the upper Mississippi. That’s where it gets a little hazy…. They don't control the Missouri, and much of the headwaters of the Mississippi are… sparsely populated at best. And we’ve received reports that their claims of dominance along the East Coast are unfounded, and they really don’t have much of a role past the Appalachian Mountains."

"And what's east of the Appalachians?" Marcus asked.

Cassia looked at Theodore.

Theodore said: "We don’t know. Reports are… unclear. We are rediscovering what was once lost. We know the old maps… we just don’t know who lives there anymore…But there are rumors of… small pockets of survivors… City-states almost. Merchant cities. There are other rumors as well… of witches, and pirates…"

The room was quiet for a moment.

"Surely, this is a fantastical Syndicate account, to scare us," said Silvanus.

"My network is reliable, Silvanus,” replied Cassia, “The scouts didn't make direct contact. They are reporting what they heard from contacts in the Syndicate. The Syndicate’s trade routes range from the bottom of the Mississippi and the Gulf Coast, all the way to Buffalo! They dwarf us by comparison! I trust my scouts, and my scouts trust their contacts. They reported evidence of technology, monastic orders, covens of witches, but with functioning technology. Old-world technology."

"What kind of technology?"

Theodore hesitated. This was the part he had been dreading. The part that sounded like myth. The part that, if it were true, changed everything.

"They reported a Terminal," he said. "A working computer. Connected to a network of some kind. And they reported... readings. Signals. Something still running in the old repositories. Something that appeared to be responding to input."

Silvanus set down his cup. It was the first time Theodore had ever seen him set down a cup.

"Responding," Silvanus said. "To what?"

"Once again, we don’t know… This is all hearsay," Theodore said. "What we know for sure is that there are rumors of pre-Collapse technology, more than what our families were able to preserve, and it’s consistently attributed to coastal enclaves east of the Appalachian Mountains. "

"My scouts would not make a report they did not truly believe," Cassia said.

"Understood." replied Senator Aretias. 

The silence that followed was not the silence of confusion. It was the silence of four people, each one of them powerful in a different way, each one of them accustomed to being the most knowledgeable person in any room they entered, confronting the possibility that they had just become the least.

“You are your scouts, Cassia!" Marcus said finally. "Had to go stirring up Syndicate trouble… why couldn’t you just stay closer to home?"

"My scouts and spies go where I command," Cassia said, calmly responding in a soft, strained voice. Her respect for Marcus halted her rage. "They're not certain what it means."

"What it means," Silvanus said, "is that we are not the only people with access to old-world technology. Before the storm. It also means that the Syndicate is only telling us what they want us to hear…” The room fell silent again.

"Who else knows?" Silvanus asked.

"The four of us. The Sag-scouts — six of them, all sworn to silence, under penalty of death. And whoever is sitting at the Terminal in Maine."

"So no one," Marcus said. "No one knows anything, and we have to decide what to do about it."

"I do not believe this Syndicate information. Look at the source. Merchants and thieves…" Theodore said.

Silvanus looked at his cup. Picked it up again. Set it down again.

"The road," he said, "just became a military necessity. Not for the Mississippi. For the Atlantic. If there's a functioning system out there — a system that survived the Collapse — we need to know what it is. We need to know who's operating it. We need to know whether it's a threat or an opportunity… this is everything our Republic is built on. Even if there’s a chance that…"

"What if it's a threat?" Marcus asked. “What if it’s a Syndicate trap?”

"Then we need to reach it before the Syndicate does," Silvanus said. "The Syndicate has better intelligence than we do. They may already know. They may already be moving."

Theodore looked at Cassia. Cassia looked back at him with the expression she always wore when someone was about to ask her to do something she was already doing. Impulsive Silvanus. Thank the Gods he wasn’t really in charge here.

"I'll increase the eastern surveillance," she said. "Double the scouts. Triple the courier frequency. If the Syndicate is moving toward the Atlantic, we'll know."

"We are overextending ourselves, Senators!" Theodore rapped the gavel and shouted. The room quieted. “We cannot possibly build a road from Amarillo to Tulsa, and somehow foray thousands of miles across the Great Plains… I understand the desire, Senators, I truly do. But is the possibility of “old-world” technology really more important than the half-million people we CARE for? They need infrastructure, food, materials. To conscript enough soldiers for a MILITARY REGIMENT travelling thousands of miles on foot, on a dream, a prayer, a hope? I will not hear it!”

Cassia didn't respond. She looked around the room. She hadn’t expected this outburst from Senator Aretias. But all she could think about was what happened if the Syndicate reached the Terminal first. The Syndicate didn't believe in temples. The Syndicate believed in control. If there was something still running in the old repositories — something that answered when spoken to — the Syndicate would either own it or destroy it.

There was no third option.

---

Later, alone in his office, Theodore stood at the window and looked out over New Platte. The city spread below him in its recovering sprawl — salvaged stone and reclaimed timber, solar arrays glittering on rooftops, the thin ribbon of the South Platte River reflecting the pale gray of the afternoon sky. Eighty thousand people. Five hundred thousand across the Republic. And if Theodore Aretias was going to protect the Republic he had inherited, he needed to be strong.

---

Chapter Three - Ouranos


---

The sky, the primordial Ouranos, was so jealous of Gaia and her creations — her beloved mankind — that he remembered how to kill.

The Gods blamed Kronos. The Titan, the Timekeeper, the Father of Olympians. One could call it retribution for that ancient scythe-cut that had split Sky-Father from Earth-Mother in the first age of the world. His revenge finally realized, Ouranos had been blanketing Gaia in a thick, killing mist for over two hundred years.

Diana knew his moods the way others once knew seasons.

Yellow-gray meant stay below. Deep orange meant the air would bite exposed skin. Black-white with electrical flickers threading through deep blues and purples meant static storms rolling through the satellite band — rare, dangerous, occasionally useful if you knew how to listen. Those were the days of Zeus: lightning without thunder first, the crack arriving late, as if the sky itself was uncertain of its own conviction.

And once in a great while — typically at the winter solstice, when Ouranos exhausted himself — the dust-plagued heavens would fracture open into pale, almost-white blue. The elder witches called it the Stellarum. The Light-that-came-before. On those days, Gaia remembered a time when Apollo showed his face daily, and the steady phases of Artemis waxed and waned, creating the mythic rhythm of the lunar calendar .  Ourea, the mountains, could be seen from hundreds of miles away, and the stars painted a celestial road across the night-sky. Ouranos had ended all that.

But that was a legend… now fading to myth.

Today was yellow-gray. Ouranos was still.

Diana wrapped her scarf twice around her mouth and stepped out of the Loom-hall into the quarry's main thoroughfare, the wide stone passage the coven called the Weft — the horizontal thread in the weave, the one that held all the others in place.

---

The Wiganmot of Witchfoot was not a government. It was not a religion. It was not a survival collective, though it performed all three functions when necessary. It was, in the language the elders used when speaking to each other rather than to the young, a *pattern.* A way of arranging human life so that it resembled something older than human life — the weave of a loom, the braid of a river, the spiral of a shell. The coven did not believe in hierarchy. It believed in *relationship.* Each person, a thread. Each thread connected to others at specific points. The whole structure held because the tension was distributed. The Weft was the Way.

Diana's mother had been a Wefanta — one of the senior women who maintained the coven's social fabric, resolving disputes, arranging apprenticeships, determining which witch would work salvage route and who would tend the wells, and who would sit vigil with the dying. It was important work. It was also, Diana had understood from a very young age, work that could consume a person entirely, leaving nothing for the children who waited in the Loom-hall for a mother who came home too tired to speak.

Her mother had died suddenly of a sickness, coughing blood when Diana was nine. The coven had absorbed the loss the way it absorbed all losses — by redistributing the threads. Diana had been assigned to the salvage track, not because anyone asked her preference, but because she had already been sneaking out to the old library for two years by then, and the elders had decided it was easier to legitimize the behavior than to forbid it.

She did not resent them for this. Resentment was a thread that pulled the whole weave out of true.

---

The Weft was busy this morning. A shipment of salvaged cloth had arrived from the southern covens — the Mousam enclave, near the old coast — and the Wefantas were sorting the fabric by color and weave, piling the sturdiest wools for the winter allotments and setting aside the finer synthetics for trade with the Porcupine islanders, who valued anything that held its shape in saltwater. The Wefantas were the coven's technical adepts, the ones who could coax another season out of a sewing machine that should have died decades ago, who could read the old pattern-books and reproduce the stitchwork of the before-time from faded diagrams. They worked in a side-chamber off the main Loom-hall, the witches called it the Seamstry. It was a long stone room with good ventilation and a dozen workstations made from salvaged desks and improvised shelving, the air thick with the smell of oiled machinery and treated wool.

Sister Verra was supervising the sorting. She was the eldest Wefanta in the coven, seventy-something by her own uncertain count, with hands that shook slightly but never made mistakes when they were holding a loom or needle. She had been the one who taught Diana to read the old-world manuals and clothing templates — not out of generosity, but because Diana had asked too many questions during a salvage briefing, and Verra had decided that the only way to shut her up was to give her enough knowledge to answer her own questions.

It had not worked. Diana had simply learned to ask better questions.

"Shipment's thin," Verra said, without looking up from the cloth she was examining. "Mousam's holding back the good ones. They always do this in the winter."

"Maybe they need the good ones themselves," Diana said.

"Mousam's got more salvage than they know what to do with. They hold back because they like watching us barter." She set the embroidered fabric down and made a mark on the slate beside her desk. "Your mother was the only one who could negotiate with them properly. They were scared of her."

Diana had heard this before. Her mother had been many things to many people. She had learned, over the years, to let the stories wash over her without catching on anything. They were not her memories. They belonged to She-Who-Is-Three now.

"Anything for me?" she asked.

Verra gestured toward a pile of components at the far end of the bench. "Capacitors. Mostly dead. Maybe one or two worth salvaging. Take them if you want them."

Diana didn't want them. But she took them anyway, because Verra was offering, and because there was always something useful to be extracted from a dead capacitor if you had the patience to find it.

---

The Loom-hall was the coven's heart.

It occupied the largest chamber in the old quarry warehouse— built in a natural cavity in the granite that had been widened by generations of patient excavation, its walls smoothed and its ceiling reinforced with salvaged steel beams. The floor was stone, worn glossy by decades of bare and booted feet. The light came from lenses — salvaged optics arranged in clusters along the walls, each one connected to a solar array on the surface by a daisy-chain of cables that the Wefantas maintained with obsessive care. Even with this invention, the ceilings were so high the light seemed to barely reach the floor. The Loom-hall looked like a shadowy, haphazard mess.

At the center of the hall stood the Looms themselves.

Twelve great looms were in a row. Twelve Wefantas could work at a time, with a novice witch as a helper at each station. The looms were gigantic — a massive frame of salvaged hardwood and forged iron, older than the coven, older than the Collapse, pulled from the ruins of a textile mill in what had once been the town of Belfast and hauled up to the quarry, one by one, by generations of witches who were now long dead. They stood ten feet tall and fifteen feet wide, its warp threads descending in a curtain of dyed wool and salvaged synthetic fiber, its shuttle moving back and forth in the hands of whichever weaver was currently on shift.

The looms were always working. The coven's clothes, blankets, tapestries, and ceremonial clothes all came from it. But more than that — the Loom was the coven's memory. Each pattern recorded something. A birth. A death. A successful salvage. A winter that nearly ended them. The weavers encoded information into the cloth the way the old world had encoded information into its machines: systematically, precisely, with layers of meaning that only the initiated could read.

Diana could read some of it. Not all of it. The full language of the Loom took decades to learn, and she had spent most of her time in the Spark-hall instead. But she knew enough to recognize the pattern that was being woven today — the spiral, the return, the thread that circled back on itself. It was the pattern for a journey completed, or a journey about to begin. The weavers never specified which.

---

She found Sister Sable in the Loom-hall's eastern alcove, where the coven kept its historical records.

Sable was the closest thing Witchfoot had to an archivist — a woman in her fifties who had lost her voice to a throat injury decades ago and now communicated through a combination of written notes, hand gestures, and a salvaged text-to-speech device that rendered her words in a flat, mechanical tone that somehow made everything she said sound like a pronouncement of doom. She was the keeper of the coven's oldest knowledge: Witchfoot scriptures, the pre-Collapse texts, the fragments of the before-time that the Wefantas had preserved across two centuries.

Diana liked her. She was one of the few people in the coven who never asked why Diana needed to know something. She simply provided the information and let Diana draw her own conclusions.

"The old network," Diana said, settling onto the bench across from Sable's workstation. "The one before the Collapse. How did it work?"

Sable's fingers moved across her text-to-speech device. The flat voice emerged: *Specify. What do you want to know about the network?*

"How it connected. How the machines talked to each other. Was it wireless? Was it wired? The elders talk about the old internet like it was magic, but Verra says it was just cables and signals. I want to know which."

Sable was quiet for a moment. Then she rose and crossed to a shelf at the back of the alcove, where a collection of preserved documents sat in sealed casings. She selected one — a thin volume, its cover worn but legible — and brought it back to the workstation.

*This is a pre-Collapse textbook,* she typed. *Introduction to Network Architecture. It explains the physical infrastructure of the old internet. Verra is correct. It was cables and signals. But the cables were extraordinary.*

Diana opened the book. The pages were brittle but intact — the sealed casing had preserved them from the acid air. Diagrams showed lines of fiber-optic cable running beneath oceans, connecting continents, carrying light through glass threads thinner than human hair.

"The sea cables," she said. "They went under the ocean?"

*Yes. They were designed to survive extreme conditions. Earthquakes. Volcanic activity. The book estimates that some of them could have survived for centuries without maintenance.*

Diana stared at the diagram. The lines ran everywhere. Across the Atlantic. Across the Pacific. Connecting every continent in a web of glass and light.

"Could they still work?" she asked. "After two hundred years?"

Sable's fingers paused over her device. Then: *Unknown. No one in the coven has attempted to access them. We have no equipment capable of interfacing with that kind of infrastructure. But the theory suggests... yes. If the cables are intact, and if a signal could be sent through them, they would still carry light.*

Diana closed the book.

She was thinking about the old stories. The Terminal the coven maintained. The Wyrd-Webbe. The machine that had been running for two centuries without anyone quite understanding what it did. The elders said it was a tool for divination — a way of reading patterns, drawing cards, interpreting the will of the gods. But Verra had told her once, late at night, when the rest of the coven was asleep, that the Wyrd-Webbe was more than that. That it was connected to something. That it had been waiting, all these years, for a signal.

Diana had not understood what she meant at the time.

She was beginning to.

---

That evening, she walked the Weft alone.

The coven was settling into its night cycle. The Wefantas had closed the Loom-hall. The weavers had draped the looms for the night. The children were being herded toward the dormitory chambers. The elders were gathering in the council alcove for their evening discussion — a ritual Diana would be expected to join when she was older, and which she avoided now with the careful indifference of someone who had no interest in governance.

She passed the shrine to the Nine — a small alcove off the main passage where the coven kept its offerings to the Muses. The shrine was older than the coven's memory. No one knew who had built it, or when. The statues were carved from local granite, their features worn almost smooth by centuries of touching hands. Calliope with her tablet. Clio with her scroll. Urania with her celestial sphere — a salvaged glass orb that caught the lens-light and scattered it across the alcove walls.

Diana did not pray. She had never been certain what prayer was supposed to accomplish, or to whom it was addressed. But she stood before the shrine for a long moment, looking at the nine worn faces, and she thought about what Sable had told her. The sea cables. The glass threads. The light that could travel through them, even now, even after everything.

And she thought about the Wyrd-Webbe. The Terminal in the old warehouse. The machine that had been running for two hundred years, but just gathered dust in the corner.

She did not touch the shrine. She did not speak. But something in her — some thread in the weave of her own being — tightened slightly, as if tugged by a hand she could not see.

*You are not supposed to be here yet.*

She didn't know where the words came from. She didn't know if they were memory or imagination or something else entirely.

But they stayed with her, repeating, as she walked back to her chamber in the Loom-hall's western corridor.

*Not yet. Not yet. Not yet.*

*But soon.*

---


